Posted by Amanda on January 09, 1997 at 21:11:36:<p>
In Reply to: <a href="975.html">Re: Science Education crisis</a> posted by Stephen Charchuk on January 09, 1997 at 10:58:24:<p>
<br>: : I was under the impression that the flame in fire was an example of what physicists call 'plasma' - it's not a gas, or a iquid, or a solid but some fourth state of matter. And, if so, it's pretty common on earth.<p>: You're correct about plasma being the most common form of matter/energy, but that is out in space, this state is actually no very common on a planetary surface.<p>So, the flame in fire isn't an example of plasma then? I'll have to do some reading on this - when will they ever stop and give me time to catch up. GOD'S TEETH!
