<textarea name="body" COLS=70 ROWS=20>
: : : Hi Lynn,

: : : I have for a long time pondered over what kind of odd fellow this christian god could be. Having created this seemingly unique entity called the human brain, with all its capability of rational thought, he then decides to condemn those who actually uses this brilliant organ. Where is the logic, the consistency in that?

: : : Now, I do not mean to say that you are not using your brain, since apparently you do. I simply would like to understand why he would discard his own fruit like that.

: : : Just curious

: : : /Lars

: : 
: : Hello Lars,
: :      I'm afraid I can't answer your point about God only condemning those who use rational thought until you expound a little.  I feel that I am a rational thinker, so I'm not sure what you mean.  
: :      It is hard to understand why God chooses some for honor and some for destruction.  I believe it is a topic that every thinking Christian must wrestle with.  The Bible, my only reference on the topic, says we have no right to judge Him for choosing between men, and asks , &quot;Does the potter not have the right to make of the clay what he chooses?  Should the creation ask the Creator, Why have you made me thus?&quot; (not a direct quote...I don't have my bible in front of me)  These are hard sayings, especially to someone who has not had personal knowledge of his loving kindness. 
: :      I was raised in a non-christian home and was pretty much an agnostic 'til I was about 20.  I did not go to church then, nor do I now. (I'm not much of a joiner)  I didn't have any christian friends trying to save me.  I was just making bad choices and leading a miserable life when I decided to open a bible that had been lying around my house since I was a kid.  For the first time, the words jumped off the page at me and melted my heart.  I truely felt His warm, loving presence in my soul.  
: :      I wish I had a great answer for you.  This one comes down to my faith in His justice, mercy and loving kindness.   I suppose that makes me irrational in your eyes. 

: I realize I might be asking the wrong person, but please let me expand a little. I posit that rational thinking is incompatible with religious faith. Or rather, _consistent_ rationality is. I also assume that free thinking is something good, that it is the way to personal and social health (read: democracy), and that it is intimately associated with rationality.

: Now, if god gave us these capabilities, and put us in these circumstances, I have trouble understanding why he should not want us to seek the truth by ourselves. Why would he want us to live by faith when this is not only clearly dangerous but also violates the only really special thing about ourselves?

: This is essentially an argument against fundamentalism, but I supppose most fundamentalists would not subscribe to my premises so it would not lead anywhere hith them. That's why I turn to a &quot;thinking christian&quot; like you. If you could expand a little on the &quot;Does the potter not have the right to make of the clay what he chooses?  Should the creation ask the Creator, Why have you made me thus?&quot; part, I would appreciate it greatly. It sounds to me like god disapproves of human rights (?!).

