<html>
  <head>
    <title>Re: The Problem of Fundamentalism in the World's Major Religions Today </title>
  </head>
  <body>
    <center>
      <h1>Re: The Problem of Fundamentalism in the World's Major Religions Today </h1>
    </center>
<hr size=7 width=75%>
<center>[ <a href="#followups">Follow Ups</a> ] [ <a href="#postfp">Post Followup</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/skepticboard.html">Skeptics Society Message Board</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/faq.html">FAQ</a> ]</center>
<hr size=7 width=75%><p>
Posted by <a href="mailto:lgrant@netonecom.net">Lynn</a> on December 12, 1996 at 13:03:59:<p>
In Reply to: <a href="500.html">Re: The Problem of Fundamentalism in the World's Major Religions Today </a> posted by Lars Berg on December 12, 1996 at 05:24:22:<p>
<br>: : : Hi Lynn,<p>: : : I have for a long time pondered over what kind of odd fellow this christian god could be. Having created this seemingly unique entity called the human brain, with all its capability of rational thought, he then decides to condemn those who actually uses this brilliant organ. Where is the logic, the consistency in that?<p>: : : Now, I do not mean to say that you are not using your brain, since apparently you do. I simply would like to understand why he would discard his own fruit like that.<p>: : : Just curious<p>: : : /Lars<p>: : <br>: : Hello Lars,<br>: :      I'm afraid I can't answer your point about God only condemning those who use rational thought until you expound a little.  I feel that I am a rational thinker, so I'm not sure what you mean.  <br>: :      It is hard to understand why God chooses some for honor and some for destruction.  I believe it is a topic that every thinking Christian must wrestle with.  The Bible, my only reference on the topic, says we have no right to judge Him for choosing between men, and asks , "Does the potter not have the right to make of the clay what he chooses?  Should the creation ask the Creator, Why have you made me thus?" (not a direct quote...I don't have my bible in front of me)  These are hard sayings, especially to someone who has not had personal knowledge of his loving kindness. <br>: :      I was raised in a non-christian home and was pretty much an agnostic 'til I was about 20.  I did not go to church then, nor do I now. (I'm not much of a joiner)  I didn't have any christian friends trying to save me.  I was just making bad choices and leading a miserable life when I decided to open a bible that had been lying around my house since I was a kid.  For the first time, the words jumped off the page at me and melted my heart.  I truely felt His warm, loving presence in my soul.  <br>: :      I wish I had a great answer for you.  This one comes down to my faith in His justice, mercy and loving kindness.   I suppose that makes me irrational in your eyes. <p>: I realize I might be asking the wrong person, but please let me expand a little. I posit that rational thinking is incompatible with religious faith. Or rather, _consistent_ rationality is. I also assume that free thinking is something good, that it is the way to personal and social health (read: democracy), and that it is intimately associated with rationality.<p><br>Dear Lars,<p>I feel that He DOES want us to think.  He says, "Come now, and let us reason together", and, "Blessed is the man that doth meditate good things in wisdom, and that reasoneth of holy things by his understanding".  It was His pleasure to give you the freedom to think in any way you choose.  If His desire was to create a bunch of robots who would blindly follow Him, He would have done so, and we wouldn't be having this conversation.   <br>     <p>: Now, if god gave us these capabilities, and put us in these circumstances, I have trouble understanding why he should not want us to seek the truth by ourselves. Why would he want us to live by faith when this is not only clearly dangerous but also violates the only really special thing about ourselves?<p><br>As I stated earlier, I sought the truth on my own, yet once I had humbled myself to the point where I was willing to say, "God, if you are real, would you please help me?" He didn't leave me alone to wonder if I was blindly following a non-existent god.  He touched my heart in a way that is so deep and real that I cannot convey it in words and has also helped me in very tangible ways, therefore, it would be irrational for me to deny his Diety.   <br>I am very thankful for the wonderful brain God has given me.  I use it quite often.<p> This is essentially an argument against fundamentalism, but I supppose most fundamentalists would not subscribe to my premises so it would not lead anywhere hith them. That's why I turn to a "thinking christian" like you. If you could expand a little on the "Does the potter not have the right to make of the clay what he chooses?  Should the creation ask the Creator, Why have you made me thus?" part, I would appreciate it greatly. It sounds to me like god disapproves of human rights (?!).<p><br>Not at all!  God's laws work for the benefit of believers and non-believers alike!  If one sows good deeds and unselfish love, he will reap the blessing, reguardless of his belief about God.  It's like the law of gravity...it works for everybody.  You have the human right to reject Him if you choose, but He has the right to reserve heaven for those who love Him.  I do not believe in hell.  "The wages of sin is death", nothing more.  <p><p><p> 
<br>
