  <body>
    <center>
      <h1>Re: The Problem of Fundamentalism in the World's Major Religions Today </h1>
    </center>
<hr size=7 width=75%>
<center>[ <a href="#followups">Follow Ups</a> ] [ <a href="#postfp">Post Followup</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/skepticboard.html">Skeptics Society Message Board</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/faq.html">FAQ</a> ]</center>
<hr size=7 width=75%><p>
Posted by <a href="mailto:Lars.Berg@genetik.uu.se">Lars Berg</a> on December 12, 1996 at 17:36:39:<p>
In Reply to: <a href="503.html">Re: The Problem of Fundamentalism in the World's Major Religions Today </a> posted by Lynn on December 12, 1996 at 13:03:59:<p>
<br>: : I realize I might be asking the wrong person, but please let me expand a little. I posit that rational thinking is incompatible with religious faith. Or rather, _consistent_ rationality is. I also assume that free thinking is something good, that it is the way to personal and social health (read: democracy), and that it is intimately associated with rationality.<p>: <br>: Dear Lars,<p>: I feel that He DOES want us to think.  He says, "Come now, and let us reason together", and, "Blessed is the man that doth meditate good things in wisdom, and that reasoneth of holy things by his understanding".  It was His pleasure to give you the freedom to think in any way you choose.  If His desire was to create a bunch of robots who would blindly follow Him, He would have done so, and we wouldn't be having this conversation.   <p>Fine. I just tend not to see how anyone could reason with a supernatural being keeping his/her mind rational, that's all.<p>: : Now, if god gave us these capabilities, and put us in these circumstances, I have trouble understanding why he should not want us to seek the truth by ourselves. Why would he want us to live by faith when this is not only clearly dangerous but also violates the only really special thing about ourselves?<p>: <br>: As I stated earlier, I sought the truth on my own, yet once I had humbled myself to the point where I was willing to say, "God, if you are real, would you please help me?" He didn't leave me alone to wonder if I was blindly following a non-existent god.  He touched my heart in a way that is so deep and real that I cannot convey it in words and has also helped me in very tangible ways, therefore, it would be irrational for me to deny his Diety.   <br>: I am very thankful for the wonderful brain God has given me.  I use it quite often.<p>I don't doubt that, please believe me. But what you're saying is, basically, that you couldn't find the truth on your own, and so god gave you a hand and showed you the truth. That's fine with me if it is for you. But you gave up you're rationality on the way. Is that a fair representation?<p>The point I would like to make is that, if instead of seeking the 'divine' advice, people would tend to accept their inability to find truth and leave it at that, the world might be a better place. Simply because rational people are reasonable, and reasonable people don't tend to opress one another and force their belief on others. This is meant in general, and not necessarily applicable to you.<p>Perhaps I am terribly impolite, please forgive me if that is the case.<p><br>::  This is essentially an argument against fundamentalism, but I supppose most fundamentalists would not subscribe to my premises so it would not lead anywhere hith them. That's why I turn to a "thinking christian" like you. If you could expand a little on the "Does the potter not have the right to make of the clay what he chooses?  Should the creation ask the Creator, Why have you made me thus?" part, I would appreciate it greatly. It sounds to me like god disapproves of human rights (?!).<p>: <br>: Not at all!  God's laws work for the benefit of believers and non-believers alike!  If one sows good deeds and unselfish love, he will reap the blessing, reguardless of his belief about God.  It's like the law of gravity...it works for everybody.<p>Only less observably :-)<p>You have the human right to reject Him if you choose, but He has the right to reserve heaven for those who love Him.  I do not believe in hell.  "The wages of sin is death", nothing more.<p>I just don't see how using the gray cells he supposedly gave us can be a violation of his will, that's all.<br>
