: : I feel that most of the people at this message board ARE searching for the truth.

: Personally I prefer the act of searching to the belief that I have actually found it. I would hope that that goes for the majority of sceptics too.

: : It seems to me that any deep thinker will ultimately wrestle with these questions.  If you have concluded that there is no God,

: Nope, I haven't. I don't see how I could possibly conclude such a thing. Do you?

: : ...I have to wonder if it's because you are disappointed with those who don't live up to your expectations of what a Christian should be, or if you feel He has deserted or hurt you in some way. Do you feel that you are being judged?  If so, I just want to tell you that He loves you.  Think of someone you know and love.  Would you sacrifice your own child for that person's life?  Neither would I.  But, even though you do not love or acknowledge Him, (really, none of us do as we should)  He made that sacrifice for YOU, and only asks that you not reject his gift.

: Well, I _have_ read the new testament, so you don't need to tell me the story. As concerns my disappointment, it does strike me as peculiar the extent to which people through western history has expressed intolerance and hatred in the name of love. I would prefer if it was done in its proper name.

: Anyway, that should have no bearing on the question of whether or not god exists, and if so, if the bible describes him correctly.

: : If you are an agnostic, wouldn't it be profitable to explore the possibility?  If God does not exist, you have lost nothing.  If He does, you have gained a great deal.

: Thanks for your concern, but I'm fine thanks :-).

