pressed intolerance and hatred in the name of love. I would prefer if it was done in its proper name.<p>: Anyway, that should have no bearing on the question of whether or not god exists, and if so, if the bible describes him correctly.<p>: : If you are an agnostic, wouldn't it be profitable to explore the possibility?  If God does not exist, you have lost nothing.  If He does, you have gained a great deal.<p>: Thanks for your concern, but I'm fine thanks :-).<p>Dear Lars,<br>I'm afraid I've offended you.  I declared that I was not proslytizing, and then I did.  Forgive me.<br>I visited your web site and I'm quite impressed.  It's a trip that a housewife in Michigan can have stimulating conversation with a highly educated student in Sweden.  <br>I wonder now if I haven't misunderstood your point.  I certainly don't think you would have to throw away everything you have learned and come to believe in order to be acceptable to God.  Why would He expect us NOT to explore the workings of nature and the universe.<br>Personally, I find no disagreement between scientific discovery and what the Bible says.  But enough of that, let's move to some other debate.  
