  <head>
    <title>Re: The Problem of Fundamentalism in the World's Major Religions Today </title>
  </head>
  <body>
    <center>
      <h1>Re: The Problem of Fundamentalism in the World's Major Religions Today </h1>
    </center>
<hr size=7 width=75%>
<center>[ <a href="#followups">Follow Ups</a> ] [ <a href="#postfp">Post Followup</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/skepticboard.html">Skeptics Society Message Board</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/faq.html">FAQ</a> ]</center>
<hr size=7 width=75%><p>
Posted by <a href="mailto:Lars.Berg@genetik.uu.se">Lars Berg</a> on December 11, 1996 at 09:32:30:<p>
In Reply to: <a href="450.html">Re: The Problem of Fundamentalism in the World's Major Religions Today </a> posted by Lynn on December 05, 1996 at 11:20:18:<p>
: I am somewhat of a "skeptic" within the Christian religion, in that I am researching the beliefs of all the various denominations, going back to the bible with an open mind, and then trying to "rightly divide the truth".<br>:      I feel that the type of fundamentalist you are describing has a great love for Jesus and is in great need of a little diplomacy.  The scripture tells us not to behave in this way.  I do believe though that these people do what they do out of a genuine love for you, and not because they want to feel superior to you.<br>:      As far as going to hell is concerned, I'm not sure there is one, although I do feel there is some sort of punishment for sure.  Perhaps it is only the knowledge that you blew it right before your conciousness ceases to exist.  It's my understanding that the wages of sin is death, and that the bible says that those who believe in Christ will have eternal life.  I have not found any indication that there is eteranl life of any sort for those who do not believe.  And as far as missing out on heaven goes, I don't think people who reject God during their lives on earth would be anymore inclined to love him in the next and, therefore, would be quite unhappy there. <br>:  <p>Hi Lynn,<p>I have for a long time pondered over what kind of odd fellow this christian god could be. Having created this seemingly unique entity called the human brain, with all its capability of rational thought, he then decides to condemn those who actually uses this brilliant organ. Where is the logic, the consistency in that?<p>Now, I do not mean to say that you are not using your brain, since apparently you do. I simply would like to understand why he would discard his own fruit like that.<p>Just curious<p>/Lars
<br>
<ul><li><a href="http://www.update.uu.se/~berg/">Lars Berg's homepage</a></ul>
