  <head>
    <title>Re: The Problem of Fundamentalism in the World's Major Religions Today </title>
  </head>
  <body>
    <center>
      <h1>Re: The Problem of Fundamentalism in the World's Major Religions Today </h1>
    </center>
<hr size=7 width=75%>
<center>[ <a href="#followups">Follow Ups</a> ] [ <a href="#postfp">Post Followup</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/skepticboard.html">Skeptics Society Message Board</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/faq.html">FAQ</a> ]</center>
<hr size=7 width=75%><p>
Posted by <a href="mailto:lgrant@netonecom.net">Lynn</a> on December 11, 1996 at 19:57:09:<p>
In Reply to: <a href="495.html">Re: The Problem of Fundamentalism in the World's Major Religions Today </a> posted by TDean on December 11, 1996 at 18:47:24:<p>
<br>: Can someone explain how they separate out fundamntalism from the rest<br>: of Christianity?  Does the term really refer to a discreet group of<br>: Christians, or are all Christians proselytize considered "fundamentalist?"<p><p>Good question.<p>I looked up fundamentalism in Webster's and it is defined as "the belief that all statements made in the Bible are literally true." and, "a movement among Protestants holding that such belief is essential to Christian faith".  <p>I believe that the Bible is inerrant, but I don't feel that the every part is meant to be taken in the literal sense.  Some of it is poetic, some is prophetic and uses a lot of symbols and metaphors, and some is quite literal.  I feel that one must believe the books have been passed from generation to generation without error in order to have trust in God's word as a roadmap for life.  I don't know if this makes me a fundamentalist or not.<p>The definition for fundamental is more fitting for my particular beliefs about the Bible.  It is defined as "anything that serves as the foundation or basis of a system of belief, as a truth, law, or principle.<p>I hope my debates with everone on this message board are not construed as proselytizing.  I love a good arguement.  I like politics too, if anybody wants to change the subject.  
<br>
