<html>
  <head>
    <title>Re: The Problem of Fundamentalism in the World's Major Religions Today </title>
  </head>
  <body>
    <center>
      <h1>Re: The Problem of Fundamentalism in the World's Major Religions Today </h1>
    </center>
<hr size=7 width=75%>
<center>[ <a href="#followups">Follow Ups</a> ] [ <a href="#postfp">Post Followup</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/skepticboard.html">Skeptics Society Message Board</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/faq.html">FAQ</a> ]</center>
<hr size=7 width=75%><p>
Posted by <a href="mailto:lgrant@netonecom.net">Lynn</a> on December 05, 1996 at 11:20:18:<p>
In Reply to: <a href="447.html">The Problem of Fundamentalism in the World's Major Religions Today </a> posted by Clay S on December 05, 1996 at 07:53:21:<p>
<br>: THE PROBLEM OF FUNDAMENTALISM IN THE WORLDS MAJOR RELIGIONS TODAY <p>: Today I had an encounter with a Christian Fundamentalist while waiting on a student of mine in a school <br>: cafeteria.  I should have known that something was a little strange about this fellow from the "blissed out" <br>: look he gave the heavens as he said a prayer before his meal.  Afterwards, he asked me what I did for a <br>: living.  I told him that I teach Philosophy and Mathematics at a particular university in the USA.  This was <br>: sufficient to open the floodgates of Fundamentalist Proselytizing Zeal.  He asked me where I was going <br>: when I died.  My response was that the question makes little sense and that when human beings die, their <br>: consciousness is extinguished like a fire when water is poured over it.  He told me that it is our relationship <br>: with Jesus Christ that is all-important.  Depending upon this crucial association, he said, our Eternal Destiny <br>: in Heaven or Hell is settled.  When I told him that I left religion up to those who were interested in it and <br>: had little interest eschatological issues of this sort myself, he felt compelled to quote scripture to the effect <br>: that "It is appointed unto every man to live once" and that  "We will all stand before the Throne of <br>: Judgment and be judged according to our relationship with Jesus."  I told him that these views were little <br>: more than anthropomorphic and childish superstitions. He did not understand the word <br>: "anthropomorphism" and was unclear as to the definition of "superstition" as well.  When  he asked me <br>: what a "superstition" was  I told him that it is a belief compounded of legend, myth and wishful thinking <br>: and hence, one which will not withstand logical, empirical, scientific and philosophical scrutiny.  This had <br>: little impact, and he proceeded to talk of Heaven again.  I told him that I am enormously unimpressed with <br>: talk about Heaven especially when such talk seems to utilize religious imagery and religious ideas right out <br>: of Hollywood movies and comic books.  Rudolph Otto ("The Idea of the Holy") and Mircea Eliade ("The <br>: Sacred and the Profane") and Pierre Hadot ("Philosophy as a Way of Life" and "Plotinus or the Simplicity <br>: of Vision") this isnt!! Moreover, when asked where Heaven is located, he seemed at a loss for an answer.  <br>: Even if he had said that Heaven is really another "plane of existence, this would have made little <br>: difference.  This is so since no one has been able to give any intelligible content to another plane of being <br>: in the first place.<p>: Friends, the Fundamentalist Mentality worldwide is a fixed mindset characterized by diverse doctrine, but <br>: with an immutable underlying structure.  Fundamentalism is little more than a sustained  ARGUMENTUM <br>: AD BACULUM - the classic appeal to force.  The underlying structure of this Mindset is that unless one <br>: affirms view X, then God, or the Cosmos, or whatever will see to it that you ETERNALLY PAY for <br>: failure to do so.  Let us review some of the classic ad Baculum arguments in the worlds religions and <br>: philosophies today:<p>: -If you fail to be a Marxist and affirm the socialist and communist doctrines, then the inexorable sweep and <br>: tide of history toward the Classless Society will relegate you, forever, into insignificance.  Moreover, the <br>: Revolution Itself may take your physical life as well!<p>: -Arminian Christians:  Unless you freely choose Gods great gift of Jesus Christ, then you will be damned to <br>: Hell forever<p>: -Calvinistic Christians:  Your eternal salvation or damnation has already been DECREED, to His infinite <br>: Glory, by God in The Inscrutable Counsels of Eternity before the very creation of the world.  He does only <br>: and precisely THAT which PLEASES Him.  If you are unwilling to be Damned for his Sparkling Glory, <br>: then you are surely among the reprobate and unelect.<p>: -Mahayana Buddhist Fundamentalists:  Unless the Mahayana Buddhist Views concerning Inherent <br>: Existence (as taught by the Omniscient Nagarjuna), along with those regarding  Compassion and Nirvana, <br>: are affirmed, one is advocating a philosophical and religious outlook characterized by either Over Negation <br>: on the one hand,  or Under Negation on the other.  Moreover, if one fails to take the Bodhisattva Vows, <br>: then one is relegated to an inferior Nirvana Forever.  <p>: -New Age Fundamentalists:  Unless you affirm that Spiritually involves Following  your Bliss to Infinite <br>: and Eternal Ecstasy along with the Omniscience and Perfection of both our Guru and our Timeless Yogic <br>: Paths,  then your are mired in delusion, hubris and Spiritual Ignorance.<p>: Please see that the Fundamentalist Mindset is not only inimical to personal and social harmony, but it is, <br>:<p><br>Hello Clay,<br>     I love your postings.  They always get me thinking!  I am somewhat of a "skeptic" within the Christian religion, in that I am researching the beliefs of all the various denominations, going back to the bible with an open mind, and then trying to "rightly divide the truth".<br>     I feel that the type of fundamentalist you are describing has a great love for Jesus and is in great need of a little diplomacy.  The scripture tells us not to behave in this way.  I do believe though that these people do what they do out of a genuine love for you, and not because they want to feel superior to you.<br>     As far as going to hell is concerned, I'm not sure there is one, although I do feel there is some sort of punishment for sure.  Perhaps it is only the knowledge that you blew it right before your conciousness ceases to exist.  It's my understanding that the wages of sin is death, and that the bible says that those who believe in Christ will have eternal life.  I have not found any indication that there is eteranl life of any sort for those who do not believe.  And as far as missing out on heaven goes, I don't think people who reject God during their lives on earth would be anymore inclined to love him in the next and, therefore, would be quite unhappy there. <br> <p><br>    
<br>
<br><hr size=7 width=75%><p>
