    <center>
      <h1>Re: Re:  Fundamentalism Today </h1>
    </center>
<hr size=7 width=75%>
<center>[ <a href="#followups">Follow Ups</a> ] [ <a href="#postfp">Post Followup</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/skepticboard.html">Skeptics Society Message Board</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/faq.html">FAQ</a> ]</center>
<hr size=7 width=75%><p>
Posted by P Suster on December 06, 1996 at 01:51:50:<p>
In Reply to: <a href="450.html">Re: The Problem of Fundamentalism in the World's Major Religions Today </a> posted by Lynn on December 05, 1996 at 11:20:18:<p>
:Hello Clay,<br>:I love your postings. They always get me thinking! I am somewhat of a "skeptic" within the Christian religion, in that I am researching the beliefs of all the various denominations, going back to the bible with an open mind, and then trying to "rightly divide the truth".<p>Greetings, Lynn.  Your posts are stimulating as well.  By why do you feel you have to "rightly divide the truth".  New phrase for me.  Is it fundamentalist Xian?<p>:I feel that the type of fundamentalist you are describing has a great love for Jesus and is in great need of a little diplomacy. The scripture tells us not to behave in this way. I do believe though that these people do what they do out of a genuine love for you, and not because they want to feel superior to you.<p>I think Clay was very diplomatic.  I would have politely told the bounder to take a hike and stop ruining my lunch.  My experience is that the vast majority of Xians who proselytize do it because of (1) their love relationship with their Master's admonishments to convert the world, and  (2) zeolotry is an emotional response, along the lines of "if misery loves company, bliss demands it." <p>:As far as going to hell is concerned, I'm not sure there is one, although I do feel there is some sort of punishment for sure.<p>Umm, confusing.  You're not sure theres's punishment when you die, (isn't that hell?) but you do feel there is some sort of punishment for sure?<p>:Perhaps it is only the knowledge that you blew it right before your conciousness ceases to exist. <p>Oh, I wrote too soon.  Perhaps a few seconds of intense regret on the lines of "Rats, I missed the cruise ship!"<p>:It's my understanding that the wages of sin is death, and that the bible says that those who believe in Christ will have eternal life. I have not found any indication that there is eteranl life of any sort for those who do not believe. <p>Now how did you arrive at these two "understandings"?  Are they based on divine revelation, or critical analysis of a broad body of evidence?  Are they based on comparative studies of a wide variety of religous/mystic inerrant revelation, or is your scope just the Bible and its myriad derivative writings?  In more mundane terms, do you buy a car or a house by just examining one item?<p>:And as far as missing out on heaven goes, I don't think people who reject God during their lives on earth would be anymore inclined to love him in the next and, therefore, would be quite unhappy there. <p>Ummm, Clay is this a variant of the _ad_baculum_ line of reasoning you were discussing above or is this something subtly different?  Personally, I'd be very happy with eternal life.  But on the light side, I'd like to do more than sing in the choir for a hundred millenia at a stretch and go "Yeeehaaaaaaa, Boss!! Smite those sinners!"  Would he let me off the hook and just let me spend eternity at the cosmic fishing hole?<p>Lynn, do you consider yourself to be a decent, honorable, loving woman? (Rhetorical question, of course you are, and it shows in your writing.) Is there any child that because of your great love you would comdemn to temporary or eternal torment just because they didn't agree that you were "Lynn" their whole life long?  If you knew of individual "X" who tormented people on that basis, would you think "X" was worthy of approval?<p>Is your vision of God such that "he" is superior to you in every quality?  If superior, why would "he" do what you in your lovingkindness would not?  If inferior, is such a deity worthy of your respect?<p>Hope I don't sound too brutal,<p>P Suster    "ubi dubium, ibi libertas"
<br>
