<html>
  <head>
    <title>Re: The Problem of Fundamentalism in the World's Major Religions Today </title>
  </head>
  <body>
    <center>
      <h1>Re: The Problem of Fundamentalism in the World's Major Religions Today </h1>
    </center>
<hr size=7 width=75%>
<center>[ <a href="#followups">Follow Ups</a> ] [ <a href="#postfp">Post Followup</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/skepticboard.html">Skeptics Society Message Board</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/faq.html">FAQ</a> ]</center>
<hr size=7 width=75%><p>
Posted by Bob Anderson on December 06, 1996 at 22:32:44:<p>
In Reply to: <a href="447.html">The Problem of Fundamentalism in the World's Major Religions Today </a> posted by Clay S on December 05, 1996 at 07:53:21:<p>
: THE PROBLEM OF FUNDAMENTALISM IN THE WORLDS MAJOR RELIGIONS TODAY <p>: Today I had an encounter with a Christian Fundamentalist while waiting on a student of mine in a school <br>: cafeteria.  I should have known that something was a little strange about this fellow from the "blissed out" <br>: look he gave the heavens as he said a prayer before his meal.  Afterwards, he asked me what I did for a <br>: living.  I told him that I teach Philosophy and Mathematics at a particular university in the USA.  This was <br>: sufficient to open the floodgates of Fundamentalist Proselytizing Zeal.  He asked me where I was going <br>: when I died.  My response was that the question makes little sense and that when human beings die, their <br>: consciousness is extinguished like a fire when water is poured over it.  He told me that it is our relationship <br>: with Jesus Christ that is all-important.  Depending upon this crucial association, he said, our Eternal Destiny <br>: in Heaven or Hell is settled.  When I told him that I left religion up to those who were interested in it and <br>: had little interest eschatological issues of this sort myself, he felt compelled to quote scripture to the effect <br>: that "It is appointed unto every man to live once" and that  "We will all stand before the Throne of <br>: Judgment and be judged according to our relationship with Jesus."  I told him that these views were little <br>: more than anthropomorphic and childish superstitions. He did not understand the word <br>: "anthropomorphism" and was unclear as to the definition of "superstition" as well.  When  he asked me <br>: what a "superstition" was  I told him that it is a belief compounded of legend, myth and wishful thinking <br>: and hence, one which will not withstand logical, empirical, scientific and philosophical scrutiny.  This had <br>: little impact, and he proceeded to talk of Heaven again.  I told him that I am enormously unimpressed with <br>: talk about Heaven especially when such talk seems to utilize religious imagery and religious ideas right out <br>: of Hollywood movies and comic books.  Rudolph Otto ("The Idea of the Holy") and Mircea Eliade ("The <br>: Sacred and the Profane") and Pierre Hadot ("Philosophy as a Way of Life" and "Plotinus or the Simplicity <br>: of Vision") this isnt!! Moreover, when asked where Heaven is located, he seemed at a loss for an answer.  <br>: Even if he had said that Heaven is really another "plane of existence, this would have made little <br>: difference.  This is so since no one has been able to give any intelligible content to another plane of being <br>: in the first place.<p>: Friends, the Fundamentalist Mentality worldwide is a fixed mindset characterized by diverse doctrine, but <br>: with an immutable underlying structure.  Fundamentalism is little more than a sustained  ARGUMENTUM <br>: AD BACULUM - the classic appeal to force.  The underlying structure of this Mindset is that unless one <br>: affirms view X, then God, or the Cosmos, or whatever will see to it that you ETERNALLY PAY for <br>: failure to do so.  Let us review some of the classic ad Baculum arguments in the worlds religions and <br>: philosophies today:<p>: -If you fail to be a Marxist and affirm the socialist and communist doctrines, then the inexorable sweep and <br>: tide of history toward the Classless Society will relegate you, forever, into insignificance.  Moreover, the <br>: Revolution Itself may take your physical life as well!<p>: -Arminian Christians:  Unless you freely choose Gods great gift of Jesus Christ, then you will be damned to <br>: Hell forever<p>: -Calvinistic Christians:  Your eternal salvation or damnation has already been DECREED, to His infinite <br>: Glory, by God in The Inscrutable Counsels of Eternity before the very creation of the world.  He does only <br>: and precisely THAT which PLEASES Him.  If you are unwilling to be Damned for his Sparkling Glory, <br>: then you are surely among the reprobate and unelect.<p>: -Mahayana Buddhist Fundamentalists:  Unless the Mahayana Buddhist Views concerning Inherent <br>: Existence (as taught by the Omniscient Nagarjuna), along with those regarding  Compassion and Nirvana, <br>: are affirmed, one is advocating a philosophical and religious outlook characterized by either Over Negation <br>: on the one hand,  or Under Negation on the other.  Moreover, if one fails to take the Bodhisattva Vows, <br>: then one is relegated to an inferior Nirvana Forever.  <p>: -New Age Fundamentalists:  Unless you affirm that Spiritually involves Following  your Bliss to Infinite <br>: and Eternal Ecstasy along with the Omniscience and Perfection of both our Guru and our Timeless Yogic <br>: Paths,  then your are mired in delusion, hubris and Spiritual Ignorance.<p>: Please see that the Fundamentalist Mindset is not only inimical to personal and social harmony, but it is, <br>: furthermore, merely a thinly veiled THREAT at best.  Not only this, but Fundamentalism is really nothing <br>: more than a "fill in the blank" mindset.  Thus the doctrines differ, but the obscurantism, intolerance and <br>: implicit violence remain the immutable structural features of this phenomenon.<p>: In closing, let me take this opportunity to invite all to construct ADEQUATE religious and philosophical <br>: visions of the world that will withstand the most rigorous moral, axiological, logical, philosophical, <br>: scientific and Authentically Contemplative scrutiny we can bring to bear upon them.<p>: Clay S.<p>Clay, I enjoyed your look at the Fundamentalist Mindset. I would like<br>to add a couple of more ideas about the Mindset, which I cannot describe<br>adequately in philosophical terms, but which I hope I can communicate.<p>First, a term you used, "wishful thinking". In terms of evangelical fundamentalist<br>Christians this is the driving force behind the view of God as a "personal God".<br>When you are in the company of believers and someone recounts an "answer to<br>prayer" it is not cool to talk about probability or the mathematics of <br>statistics, or even about the circular logic of accepting yes, no, or maybe<br>as legitimate answers from the so called "God of the Universe". Wishful<br>thinking, in my opinion, is what sustains belief in the personal interaction<br>of God in the believers life.<p>The second appeal, and whether it is inherent to all "fundamentalisms" I <br>don't know, is the appeal of absolutes.  I think this is related to the<br>"Argumentum Ad Baculum" you describe, but also has to do with the nature<br>of the mind perhaps. The Christian fundamentalism subscribes to a God who<br>is absolute in every way. Omnipotent, omnipresent, omniscient, all loving, perfectly<br>just, eternal, etc. The appeal of this is as old as religion itself, the<br>perfect answer to all that is unknown. Just as the human mind tries to<br>understand "how things work" perhaps there also is a desire for an <br>answer that is not an answer, ie. an "absolute God belief".<br>
<br>
<br><hr size=7 width=75%><p>
