  <head>
    <title>Art Bell vs Skepticism</title>
  </head>
  <body>
    <center>
      <h1>Art Bell vs Skepticism</h1>
    </center>
<hr size=7 width=75%>
<center>[ <a href="#followups">Follow Ups</a> ] [ <a href="#postfp">Post Followup</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/skepticboard.html">Skeptics Society Message Board</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/faq.html">FAQ</a> ]</center>
<hr size=7 width=75%><p>
Posted by <a href="mailto:cnjohns@sirius.com">Chris Johnson</a> on January 02, 1997 at 07:39:05:<p>
I've visited Art Bell's Web Site and it seems the opposite of skepicism: unfiltered credibility. UFOs, Roswell, fragments of "unearthly" metals (in Art's Parts section)... Chupacabras monsters etc... <p>His nationally syndicated radio show is devoted to all sorts of unexplained phenonema, most of which is accepted at face value. The whole thing seems designed to spread ignorance and progagate urban rumors. <p>The concepts of gigantic structures on the moon, supposedly visible on astronauts' photographs are another example.<p>When the year 2000 hits, it's going to be a real mess because so many folks believe enormous changes must occur due to the "new millenium."<p>It's scary to live in a "modern civilization" that doesn't operate much differently from midieval ages in the way people think and act.<p>I was hoping Art Bell would test some of these things and announce that they were frauds or rumors... sadly, not true at all.
<br>
<br><hr size=7 width=75%><p>
