Posted by <a href="mailto:kbaker@acadiacom.net">Jeff</a> on January 02, 1997 at 10:17:03:<p>
In Reply to: <a href="524.html">Re: What would a rationalist society look like?</a> posted by Philippa on December 16, 1996 at 01:04:43:<p>
 <br>: : I'm curious to know what a society run by atheists <br>: would look like? <br>: : What holidays would you celebrate?  Would you have <br>: charities?  Whom would they serve? <br>: : What would happen to religious art or church <br>: buildings?  How would you avoid becoming as <br>: : brutal as Nazi Germany or the Soviet Union?  I <br>: don't know of anywhere else I can ask these <br>: : questions and get a reasonable answer, and I don't <br>: see that anyone has examined this much.  <p><p>I couldn't find the orginal message, so I had to use this <br>thread, I'm really reponding to the person asking about a <br>atheist society.  I'm assuming you mean a society that is <br>prodominatyly atheistic or not religous, as opposed to this society<br>where most believe in God.  A few years ago, there was a study done <br>on what people thought about evolution.  The percentage of the U.S. <br>population that believed in Darwinian evolution at that point was 9%.<br>About half the population believed in divinely-guided evolution, the <br>Catholic church doctrine.  About 40% thought the world was created a <br>few thousand years ago.  In a diffrent study about three quarters of <br>Americans literally believe in religious miracles, as well as high<br>numbers who believe in the devil, in resurrection, etc.  As I <br>understand these are high numbers for an industral society.  I <br>haven't seen the numbers myself, nor have I seen numbers in Europe,<br>but if this is write, we might already have atheistic societies in <br>Europe.  To be a just society, there would have to be to the socity<br>than just being atheist.  Like you pointed out, the Soviet Union was<br>an atheist society (at least those in control were atheist).  Atheism <br>seems to me to be more of a symtom of a rationally open-minded person.<br>You can be an athiest and not be rational or open-minded.  anyway, I <br>will try to approach the question about an atheist society with the <br>idea in mind that we are also talking about a place where desent<br>people would want to live.<p>This is a very interesting question for me because not only am I a <br>Skeptic, but also a human rights activist.  This question seems to <br>come up in human right cirles that I travel.  The main problem with <br>this question is that in science we want to see many examples over <br>and over again to see what works in reality and what is just a <br>hypothsis.  Considering that most hypothsis are proven wrong, <br>thus a hypothisis, in and of itself, is not worth much.<br>It would be arrogant to think we have an definit answer to this <br>question.  So any hypothsis as to how a future society should be set <br>up, where a desent, rational person would wish to live, should be <br>threated with skeptism! (of course)  <p>     The idea of that I like most are those that are refered to as <br>Libratain Socialism.  In comes out of the classical libratarinism. <br>Not to be confussed with the U.S. 'Libratarins'.  These ideas come <br>out of the ideas of people like Adam Smith and Thomus Jefferson, etc..  <br>The basic premise is that all authority needs justification, and it <br>is up to the authority to justify itself.  If it cannot, then it must<br>be challenged and dismantaled. (Best if replaced or turned into a <br>democraticly ran instatusion.)  Sometimes an authority can bare the<br>burden, like the authority of the parent over the child (in many way<br>at least).  If my sisters kid goes to run in a busy street, I will use <br>force to stop the her, which is justified, I think.<br>   A common conserns among libratarin socialist (and progressive <br>people alike) is corperations.  In Sagan's Demon-Haunted World, he <br>mapped out the problem most Libratarin Socialist have with <br>corperations.  There is little in the way of modivation to correct <br>their errors, and sometime insentives non to correct errors.  For <br>example, DuPont can claim that thier produce don't contribute to Ozone <br>depletion at all. <br>                      How convenient!  <br>They claiming that the idea that their product is contributing Oxone <br>depletion is 'theratical'.  Well sure, but there is only one way to<br>be 100% certain and that is to destroy our atmosphere with their <br>chemicals in a number of controled experenments.  Sense we cannot do <br>that, being only one atmostfer to test and the stakes are extremly <br>high and most evendence is pointing to it being a cause, we <br>shouldn't take the risk, but their instatution cannot make that <br>decision for economic reasons.  They use their influence in <br>politics to make it hard to change decision that effect them.  This <br>is only one example, I'm sure we all know many more.<p>     As far as Holidays the society would have;  If the society <br>desided that it didn't want to follow the thaditional holidays there <br>are other options.  (BTW - I know atheist that celibrate Christmas, <br>not because of Christ, but because it is a day for family and <br>friends to come together, at least in therory.)  The other options <br>could be the celibration of human rights victory, like Martain Luther<br>King Day or May Day (A Europen Holiday to celibrate the U.S. workers <br>struggle to win the 40 hour work week), or we could celibrate <br>scientific achievements like the day when the first man walked on the <br>moon.  (I don't believe I ever heard of a day to celibrate scientific<br>acheviment.  Maybe there is none because we don't live in a <br>scientificly literate society?)<p>     Anyway, for more information on Libratarin Socialism and there <br>view of a furtue society, Read Peter Krpotkin's work (A scientist of <br>Geographical exploration.  He was also an opponent to the Social<br>Dawinist of the time.)  <p>For a more Moderin writer, read Proffessor Noam Chomsky's works.  He<br>is a world renown scientist, often refered to as the Einstein of <br>modern ligistics.  New York Time once refered to him as 'aguably the <br>most importent intellecal alive'  He is also the most cited auther <br>alive.  Beyond all of this, he is a human rights champaign.  He <br>doesn't get must press in the U.S. because of his opposition to <br>U.S. forign and domestic policies.  Probibly the most important <br>advacat on libratainsocalism.  Some of his works are on the web, <br>under Z-net.<p>http://www.worldmedia.com/archive/index.html<p>jeff<p>p.s.- I'm dyslexic, hence the inevitable errors in my writting.<br>
