  <head>
    <title>Re: Validating scientific discovery-some answers.  </title>
  </head>
  <body>
    <center>
      <h1>Re: Validating scientific discovery-some answers.  </h1>
    </center>
<hr size=7 width=75%>
<center>[ <a href="#followups">Follow Ups</a> ] [ <a href="#postfp">Post Followup</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/skepticboard.html">Skeptics Society Message Board</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/faq.html">FAQ</a> ]</center>
<hr size=7 width=75%><p>
Posted by Jason on December 27, 1996 at 01:08:37:<p>
In Reply to: <a href="520.html">Re: Validating scientific discovery-some answers.  </a> posted by Lynn on December 15, 1996 at 18:02:04:<p>
<br>: : I might be late in this discussion but some experiments you might not<br>: : be aware of - Pulling particles out of the vacuum a nuclear experiment.<br>: : Virtual particles in quantum electromagnetic theory have been <br>: : confirmed.<br>: : The Big Bang theory calls for a universe that created itself. This is no<br>: : big stunt anymore since self creation can be whitnessed in many labs.<br>: : Apparently the initial point was nothing. Some time later and therafter<br>: : the positive rest mass plus kinetic energy was canceled by the <br>: : negative gravitational potential energy so today it still adds up to<br>: : nothing. Information like writing on ice can be easily erased and that<br>: : is what our planet is made of.<br>: : For a more rigorous treatment write me at pk3.14@juno.com.<br>: : Charles <p>: Dear Charles,<p>: You're talkin' way over my head.  Can you put your argument in laymen's terms?<p><br>Hi Lynn,<p>Perhaps I can be of some help.  Big Bang cosmology interests me and I enjoy reading<br>about the arguments both pro and con for theistic involvement. Perhaps you've heard<br>of the kalam cosmological argument by the Christian apologist, William Lane Craig.<br>Generally, I've noticed three ways in which people come to non-theistic conclusions<br>of the Big Bang theory. One is from quantum vacuum fluctuations, some of Stephen<br>Hawking's arguments and the attributes of a singularity.<p>Some physicists think the Big Bang was similar to what happens when you have a<br>"quantum fluctuation." In studies of quantum mechanics, it has been found that<br>elementary particle pairs can literally appear out of nothing in empty space. Under <br>normal conditions, the positive and negative particles of the pair will annihilate <br>each other and disappear back into the vacuum. However, in curved space such as a<br>black hole, one particle will fall into the black hole while the other particle<br>escapes. The first law of thermodynamics (i.e., energy cannot be created or destroyed)<br>is not violated because the particle falling into the black hole contributes "negative<br>energy". The positive energy is in the form of the escaping particle (this is how black<br>holes emit radiation). Isn't the universe a fascinating place? I don't fully <br>understand how physicists connect this phenonenon to Big Bang cosmology but it does<br>illustrate that something can come out of nothing without divine intervention.<p>Another argument was put forth by physicist Stephen Hawking. He argued that the<br>universe did not actually begin in a singularity but that the universe is finite but<br>unbounded in time.  An analogy would be a sphere. The sphere is finite but it has no<br>point of beginning. This implies that the universe always existed and that no creator<br>is necessary.<p>Finally, if the Big Bang did begin in a singulariy, I think theism becomes<br>problematic. At a singularity, you have a state of quantum flux where time does not<br>exist. Phrases such as "before the Big Bang" become meaningless. Since terms such as<br>"creation" or "beginning" are contingent upon the notion of time, it becomes<br>problematic.<p>Hope this helps. :)<br>- Jason
<br>
<br><hr size=7 width=75%><p>
