<a name="postfp">Post a Followup</a><p>
<form method=POST action="http://www.skeptic.com/cgi-local/skepticboard.pl">
<input type=hidden name="followup" value="259,320,332,335,336,417,449,477,479,516,520,592">
<input type=hidden name="origname" value="Jason">
<input type=hidden name="origsubject" value="Re: Validating scientific discovery-some answers.  ">
<input type=hidden name="origdate" value="December 27, 1996 at 01:08:37">
Name: <input type=text name="name" size=50><br>
E-Mail: <input type=text name="email" size=50><p>
Subject: <input type=text name="subject"value="Re: Validating scientific discovery-some answers.  " size=50><p>
Comments:<br>
<textarea name="body" COLS=70 ROWS=20>
: 
: : : I might be late in this discussion but some experiments you might not
: : : be aware of - Pulling particles out of the vacuum a nuclear experiment.
: : : Virtual particles in quantum electromagnetic theory have been 
: : : confirmed.
: : : The Big Bang theory calls for a universe that created itself. This is no
: : : big stunt anymore since self creation can be whitnessed in many labs.
: : : Apparently the initial point was nothing. Some time later and therafter
: : : the positive rest mass plus kinetic energy was canceled by the 
: : : negative gravitational potential energy so today it still adds up to
: : : nothing. Information like writing on ice can be easily erased and that
: : : is what our planet is made of.
: : : For a more rigorous treatment write me at pk3.14@juno.com.
: : : Charles 

: : Dear Charles,

: : You're talkin' way over my head.  Can you put your argument in laymen's terms?

: 
: Hi Lynn,

: Perhaps I can be of some help.  Big Bang cosmology interests me and I enjoy reading
: about the arguments both pro and con for theistic involvement. Perhaps you've heard
: of the kalam cosmological argument by the Christian apologist, William Lane Craig.
: Generally, I've noticed three ways in which people come to non-theistic conclusions
: of the Big Bang theory. One is from quantum vacuum fluctuations, some of Stephen
: Hawking's arguments and the attributes of a singularity.

: Some physicists think the Big Bang was similar to what happens when you have a
: &quot;quantum fluctuation.&quot; In studies of quantum mechanics, it has been found that
: elementary particle pairs can literally appear out of nothing in empty space. Under 
: normal conditions, the positive and negative particles of the pair will annihilate 
: each other and disappear back into the vacuum. However, in curved space such as a
: black hole, one particle will fall into the black hole while the other particle
: escapes. The first law of thermodynamics (i.e., energy cannot be created or destroyed)
: is not violated because the particle falling into the black hole contributes &quot;negative
: energy&quot;. The positive energy is in the form of the escaping particle (this is how black
: holes emit radiation). Isn't the universe a fascinating place? I don't fully 
: understand how physicists connect this phenonenon to Big Bang cosmology but it does
: illustrate that something can come out of nothing without divine intervention.

: Another argument was put forth by physicist Stephen Hawking. He argued that the
: universe did not actually begin in a singularity but that the universe is finite but
: unbounded in time.  An analogy would be a sphere. The sphere is finite but it has no
: point of beginning. This implies that the universe always existed and that no creator
: is necessary.

: Finally, if the Big Bang did begin in a singulariy, I think theism becomes
: problematic. At a singularity, you have a state of quantum flux where time does not
: exist. Phrases such as &quot;before the Big Bang&quot; become meaningless. Since terms such as
: &quot;creation&quot; or &quot;beginning&quot; are contingent upon the notion of time, it becomes
: problematic.

: Hope this helps. :)
: - Jason

</textarea>
