<html>
  <head>
    <title>Re: creationism...Why is it necessary to refute Creationism in order to validate scientific discovery.  Of all people, scientists should find it impossible to believe otherwise.  The complexities of nature show that there is surely a Grand Designer.  To me, it's very hard to imagine that the universe appeared out of nothing and created itself.  Perhpaps scientists are merely discovering the means by which God did the creating.</title>
  </head>
  <body>
    <center>
      <h1>Re: creationism...Why is it necessary to refute Creationism in order to validate scientific discovery.  Of all people, scientists should find it impossible to believe otherwise.  The complexities of nature show that there is surely a Grand Designer.  To me, it's very hard to imagine that the universe appeared out of nothing and created itself.  Perhpaps scientists are merely discovering the means by which God did the creating.</h1>
    </center>
<hr size=7 width=75%>
<center>[ <a href="#followups">Follow Ups</a> ] [ <a href="#postfp">Post Followup</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/skepticboard.html">Skeptics Society Message Board</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/faq.html">FAQ</a> ]</center>
<hr size=7 width=75%><p>
Posted by <a href="mailto:crockfor@dowco.com">Peter Crockford</a> on December 02, 1996 at 02:51:51:<p>
In Reply to: <a href="336.html">Re: creationism...Why is it necessary to refute Creationism in order to validate scientific discovery.  Of all people, scientists should find it impossible to believe otherwise.  The complexities of nature show that there is surely a Grand Designer.  To me, it's very hard to imagine that the universe appeared out of nothing and created itself.  Perhpaps scientists are merely discovering the means by which God did the creating.</a> posted by Lynn on November 20, 1996 at 17:20:58:<p>
No Victoria, there isn't a Santa Claus.  Nature is a grand old show, to be sure.  Full of nooks and crannies we never could have imagined, even in our right minds.  Exciting new discoveries around every corner.  Our pathetic little twelve pound monkey brains try so valiantly to keep up.  Huff.  Puff.  Pass me that Prozac or I'll blow your house down.  But, alas, the scope of the endeavor is truly, madly, deeply, way beyond our capacity to begin imagining.  A=B: B=C: therefore A=C.  Sure, that's okay for moving a rhomboid around a point on a graph, but as far as accurately describing a dynamic, evolving, chaotic, system of staggering complexity, well, let's just say "Pathetically Inadequate" and leave it at that.  You could strap Marlon Perkins into a helicopter and forcefeed him Gatorade and banana Power Bars for the next thousand years, all the while ceaselessly circling the globe, and you still would not have witnessed one tenth of the crazy little dramas that unfold throughout Nature continuously.  Nature!  Heck, why stop there?  The Cosmos.  The unbounded, unfathomable expanse of space/time.  The fact that Nature's complexities remain more than a match for the fitful spark of human understanding should come as no surprise.  Sure, we've come up with some pretty impressive (by our standards) theories in this last hundred years or so, but many of our most revolutionary breakthroughs only lead us to equally more impressive conundrums.  Like where quantum theory informs us that if no one's in the forest to witness the falling of the famous tree, then not only are we unsure of the noise it may have generated, but we can't even say for certain that the forest exists at all.  Thus I am at ease with my ignorance.  In fact, I flaunt it.  "I have no truck with the inner workings of the universe", I tell people, "So don't come to me when the lights go out".  I do not suffer the need to have "It" all wrapped up for me in a pretty box with a big bow and curly ribbons on top.  And the fact that it's all beyond the limits of my puny brainpower most certainly does not lead me to assign some kind of Creator, or Prime Mover category at the root of it all.  In fact, just the opposite, because by imposing a human, limited, concept of "God" over top of everything, all I effectively accomplish is to thrust my own limitations over the boundless universe.  Sure it's complex.  Why does that mean somebody had to design it?  Sure, it's hard to imagine it appearing out of nowhere.  So what?  Am I then justified in saying "Because it's beyond my personal powers of comprehension, well then, here's how it was done--I'll leave the details to your imagination, of course."  No thanks.  I'm not that arrogant.  
<br>
<br><hr size=7 width=75%><p>
