<html>
  <head>
    <title>Re: Tai Chi</title>
  </head>
  <body>
    <center>
      <h1>Re: Tai Chi</h1>
    </center>
<hr size=7 width=75%>
<center>[ <a href="#followups">Follow Ups</a> ] [ <a href="#postfp">Post Followup</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/skepticboard.html">Skeptics Society Message Board</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/faq.html">FAQ</a> ]</center>
<hr size=7 width=75%><p>
Posted by Sean on January 05, 1997 at 01:43:23:<p>
In Reply to: <a href="812.html">Tai Chi</a> posted by Jason on January 04, 1997 at 00:49:52:<p>
: Does anyone know much about Tai Chi? I've heard some claims that<br>: Tai Chi masters have paranormal abilities. For example, one claim<br>: is that a Tai Chi master can immobilize an attacker simply by pointing<br>: at him. Naturally, I'm skeptical of these claims.<p>: I guess if Tai Chi masters did have extraordinary abilities, it may<br>: not necessarily be a supernatural or spiritual phenomenon. It may be<br>: some physical effect that we have yet to understand scientifically.<br>: - Jason<p><br>Having wasted a few years now, on and off, on tai chi, I can offer you<br>my opinion.  Tai Chi is a good exercise for elderly people who are<br>starting to loose their balance.  It teaches body awareness, and may<br>prevent someone from falling and breaking a hip.  There is no aerobic<br>benefit.<p>As far as developing paranormal abilities, the martial arts is filled<br>with self-delusion.  People trying to transform thenselves into <br>supermen.  I have seen a kung fu "master" get seriously stomped in<br>a bar fight with a larger person.  If this stuff was possible to any<br>degree, law enforcement and military people would have figured it <br>out by now.<p>So save yourself the time, unless you are someone who has trouble<br>unwinding.  If, like me, you are trying to "cultivate a vigorous <br>spirit", stay well away from it.
<br>
<br><hr size=7 width=75%><p>
