  <body>
    <center>
      <h1>Re: Why are Skeptic books so hard to find?</h1>
    </center>
<hr size=7 width=75%>
<center>[ <a href="#followups">Follow Ups</a> ] [ <a href="#postfp">Post Followup</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/skepticboard.html">Skeptics Society Message Board</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/faq.html">FAQ</a> ]</center>
<hr size=7 width=75%><p>
Posted by Ray Briggs on December 07, 1996 at 18:40:47:<p>
In Reply to: <a href="457.html">Why are Skeptic books so hard to find?</a> posted by Ann Friedrich on December 06, 1996 at 16:34:25:<p>
: Does anyone have any theses as to why Skeptical books<br>: are so hard to find, especially compared to the thousands<br>: of true-believer ones?<p>I think it is relatively easy to understand why there is a plethora of true-believers books and a dearth of skeptical books. Consider that believer-books typically tell people that there is an infinitely powerful creator that has a personal interest in you and that you will not die but be incredibly happy with Him for all eternity. We skeptics tell them that this is it and there probably is no such wonderful being and the idea you will be exstatically happy with Her for all eternity is simply a myth. Which message has sales appeal?<p>
<br>
<br><hr size=7 width=75%><p>
