<html>
  <head>
    <title>Re: Unlikely Existence of God</title>
  </head>
  <body>
    <center>
      <h1>Re: Unlikely Existence of God</h1>
    </center>
<hr size=7 width=75%>
<center>[ <a href="#followups">Follow Ups</a> ] [ <a href="#postfp">Post Followup</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/skepticboard.html">Skeptics Society Message Board</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/faq.html">FAQ</a> ]</center>
<hr size=7 width=75%><p>
Posted by <a href="mailto:kakadoo@sprynet.com">Amanda</a> on December 29, 1996 at 17:06:38:<p>
In Reply to: <a href="619.html">Re: Unlikely Existence of God</a> posted by Stephen Charchuk on December 29, 1996 at 01:12:52:<p>
<br>: : I believe that the Bible IS the word of God.  It is my guidebook for truth.  Not everyone agrees with me, what can I say?<p>: How much of the actual history of the putting together, chosing, and editing of the books in the bible to you know?<p>If the bible is the word of God Lynn, which there is much evidence against, how can you possibly love a God that inspired such words? You will not find anywhere else in ancient writings women treated with more contempt and disdain than in those inspired fables. God tells Moses that a woman who gives birth will be unclean for seven days if it is a male child, two weeks if it is a female child and either/or she must at the end of her confinement make a sin offering - it also tells in great detail that all that she touches or all that touches her during this time will be unclean. Women of the bible are synonymous with slaves and domestic animals. Paul - the founder of Christianity has a philosphy that basically states - any male fool is even superior than the most intelligent of women. He also says "Let a woman learn in quietness with all subjection. But I permit not a woman to teach, nor to have dominion over a man, but to be in quietness...Let the woman keep silence in the churches; for it is not permitted unto them to speak. But let them be in subjection as also saith the law. And if they would learn anything, let them ask their own husband at home; for it is shameful for a woman to speak in the church." There's another line in there somewhere that was supposedly inspired by God that goes "Fierce is the dragon and cunning the asp; but woman has the malice of both." As I'm sure you know, one of the big steps that helped Christianity become the super power it has is when it was embraced by the Roman Emperor Constantine - before then Roman law was quite favorable to women but with Christianity this was all modified extremely. The most obstacles that were put in the way of woman's legal emancipation was from the church. The condemnation of women as a sex, the attributing to her of everthing that is vile, hateful and malicious, was responsible for the witch burnings that I'm sure you're familiar with. The Christian Church was responsible for 9 MILLION women being burned for sorcery and my educated guess is that not one of those women were witches. It was believed then that women were in league with the devil, they were the cause of plagues, epidemics, misfortunes, calamities, disasters. Solomon says "What is woman but an enemy of friendship, an aviodable punishment, a necessary evil, a natural temptation, a desirable affliction, a constantly flowing source of tears, a wicked work of nature covered with a shining varnish?" As you can see I hope, the bible is the cause of the oppression of women and the attitudes that still prevail today. Ask yourself what Christianity has done for women and if you still claim to be one - please, tell me your reasons.
<br>
