<html>
  <head>
    <title>Re: Unlikely Existence of God</title>
  </head>
  <body>
    <center>
      <h1>Re: Unlikely Existence of God</h1>
    </center>
<hr size=7 width=75%>
<center>[ <a href="#followups">Follow Ups</a> ] [ <a href="#postfp">Post Followup</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/skepticboard.html">Skeptics Society Message Board</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.skeptic.com/skepticboard/faq.html">FAQ</a> ]</center>
<hr size=7 width=75%><p>
Posted by Lynn on December 30, 1996 at 01:45:36:<p>
In Reply to: <a href="629.html">Re: Unlikely Existence of God</a> posted by Amanda on December 29, 1996 at 17:06:38:<p>
<p>: <br>: : : I believe that the Bible IS the word of God.  It is my guidebook for truth.  Not everyone agrees with me, what can I say?<p>: : How much of the actual history of the putting together, chosing, and editing of the books in the bible to you know?<p>: If the bible is the word of God Lynn, which there is much evidence against, how can you possibly love a God that inspired such words? You will not find anywhere else in ancient writings women treated with more contempt and disdain than in those inspired fables. God tells Moses that a woman who gives birth will be unclean for seven days if it is a male child, two weeks if it is a female child and either/or she must at the end of her confinement make a sin offering - it also tells in great detail that all that she touches or all that touches her during this time will be unclean. Women of the bible are synonymous with slaves and domestic animals. Paul - the founder of Christianity has a philosphy that basically states - any male fool is even superior than the most intelligent of women. He also says "Let a woman learn in quietness with all subjection. But I permit not a woman to teach, nor to have dominion over a man, but to be in quietness...Let the woman keep silence in the churches; for it is not permitted unto them to speak. But let them be in subjection as also saith the law. And if they would learn anything, let them ask their own husband at home; for it is shameful for a woman to speak in the church." There's another line in there somewhere that was supposedly inspired by God that goes "Fierce is the dragon and cunning the asp; but woman has the malice of both." As I'm sure you know, one of the big steps that helped Christianity become the super power it has is when it was embraced by the Roman Emperor Constantine - before then Roman law was quite favorable to women but with Christianity this was all modified extremely. The most obstacles that were put in the way of woman's legal emancipation was from the church. The condemnation of women as a sex, the attributing to her of everthing that is vile, hateful and malicious, was responsible for the witch burnings that I'm sure you're familiar with. The Christian Church was responsible for 9 MILLION women being burned for sorcery and my educated guess is that not one of those women were witches. It was believed then that women were in league with the devil, they were the cause of plagues, epidemics, misfortunes, calamities, disasters. Solomon says "What is woman but an enemy of friendship, an aviodable punishment, a necessary evil, a natural temptation, a desirable affliction, a constantly flowing source of tears, a wicked work of nature covered with a shining varnish?" As you can see I hope, the bible is the cause of the oppression of women and the attitudes that still prevail today. Ask yourself what Christianity has done for women and if you still claim to be one - please, tell me your reasons.<p><br>Quite frankly, I think God was doing women a favor.  Do you think they were treated as equals before the law was handed down?  Get real.  These people were barbarians.  The last thing a woman wants when she's on her period or just given birth, is some smelly nomad foisting himself upon her. <br>The quote sited by Solomon surely reflects the thoughts of any man who's been burned.  This also is not a description of a godly woman.<br>Perhaps you should also ready the Songs of Solomon or some of the many other passages that speak of women in the most affectionate terms.<br>Now...I will not disagree with anyone that the CAtholic church has done many horrible things.  They claim to be the first church, but I merely see them as the first government sanctioned church.  They  mixed Christianity with the pagan religions of Rome.  Christmas is a good example.  Besides, in those times, I'm sure it wasn't only christians who were ignorant and misguided.  Also, people were illiterate, and even if they could read, would not have had access to a bible in those times.  The teachings of a corrupt church were all they had.  You'll have to admit, that things are different now.<p><br>
<br>
<br><hr size=7 width=75%><p>
