Posted by Lynn on December 30, 1996 at 10:23:21:<p>
In Reply to: <a href="639.html">Re: Unlikely Existence of God</a> posted by Amanda on December 30, 1996 at 03:25:11:<p>
<p><br>: : : <br>: : : : : I believe that the Bible IS the word of God.  It is my guidebook for truth.  Not everyone agrees with me, what can I say?<p>: : : : How much of the actual history of the putting together, chosing, and editing of the books in the bible to you know?<p>: : : If the bible is the word of God Lynn, which there is much evidence against, how can you possibly love a God that inspired such words? You will not find anywhere else in ancient writings women treated with more contempt and disdain than in those inspired fables. God tells Moses that a woman who gives birth will be unclean for seven days if it is a male child, two weeks if it is a female child and either/or she must at the end of her confinement make a sin offering - it also tells in great detail that all that she touches or all that touches her during this time will be unclean. Women of the bible are synonymous with slaves and domestic animals. Paul - the founder of Christianity has a philosphy that basically states - any male fool is even superior than the most intelligent of women. He also says "Let a woman learn in quietness with all subjection. But I permit not a woman to teach, nor to have dominion over a man, but to be in quietness...Let the woman keep silence in the churches; for it is not permitted unto them to speak. But let them be in subjection as also saith the law. And if they would learn anything, let them ask their own husband at home; for it is shameful for a woman to speak in the church." There's another line in there somewhere that was supposedly inspired by God that goes "Fierce is the dragon and cunning the asp; but woman has the malice of both." As I'm sure you know, one of the big steps that helped Christianity become the super power it has is when it was embraced by the Roman Emperor Constantine - before then Roman law was quite favorable to women but with Christianity this was all modified extremely. The most obstacles that were put in the way of woman's legal emancipation was from the church. The condemnation of women as a sex, the attributing to her of everthing that is vile, hateful and malicious, was responsible for the witch burnings that I'm sure you're familiar with. The Christian Church was responsible for 9 MILLION women being burned for sorcery and my educated guess is that not one of those women were witches. It was believed then that women were in league with the devil, they were the cause of plagues, epidemics, misfortunes, calamities, disasters. Solomon says "What is woman but an enemy of friendship, an aviodable punishment, a necessary evil, a natural temptation, a desirable affliction, a constantly flowing source of tears, a wicked work of nature covered with a shining varnish?" As you can see I hope, the bible is the cause of the oppression of women and the attitudes that still prevail today. Ask yourself what Christianity has done for women and if you still claim to be one - please, tell me your reasons.<p>: : <br>: : Quite frankly, I think God was doing women a favor.  Do you think they were treated as equals before the law was handed down?  Get real.  These people were barbarians.  The last thing a woman wants when she's on her period or just given birth, is some smelly nomad foisting himself upon her. <br>: : The quote sited by Solomon surely reflects the thoughts of any man who's been burned.  This also is not a description of a godly woman.<br>: : Perhaps you should also ready the Songs of Solomon or some of the many other passages that speak of women in the most affectionate terms.<br>: : Now...I will not disagree with anyone that the CAtholic church has done many horrible things.  They claim to be the first church, but I merely see them as the first government sanctioned church.  They  mixed Christianity with the pagan religions of Rome.  Christmas is a good example.  Besides, in those times, I'm sure it wasn't only christians who were ignorant and misguided.  Also, people were illiterate, and even if they could read, would not have had access to a bible in those times.  The teachings of a corrupt church were all they had.  You'll have to admit, that things are different now.<p>: There are many examples from the pre-christian era where women were treated as equals to men and in some instances they were even thought on higher terms. Many, many, many. Sure there were  a few nasties here and there but if your claiming that the world was a bunch of barbarians before the Christian era then dang it girl, you need to read some history books. Though the Greeks aren't known for their high opinion of women they certainly weren't barbarians - they are responsible for the beginnings of science which was then stiffled for many centuries thanks to the Godly Christians but luckily the Arabs saved the day and with the enlightenment and the reduction in church power - we saw thinking again in the Western World. I wonder how more advanced we'd be now if Christianity hadn't suppressed it in the first place.  <br>: Back to women - in Sparta women were brought up as equals to men - Plato in his writing, makes no distinction between the sexes - in Egypt, women were thought of highly - pre-Christian Rome - the uncivilized Teutonic tribes even treated their women with esteem and confidence. Christianity undoubtedly made life much worse for women - this to me is something I am not skeptic about whatsoever. If you've read your old testament, you'll see that polygamy was quite a popular thing - the Ten Commandments were written for men - over and over again women are the lowest of the low and of course they are the ones responisble for the Fall and must pay, pay, pay. Do you truly believe that the pain of labor is something that God created? Medical science has long ago solved that mystery. And if you do follow the bible then you contradict yourself because it was God who made menstruation and painful labors in the first place - before then it was all a joyous experience so a smelly nomad wouldn't cause all that much grief.<br>: Though the Songs of Solomon are well-written and almost as nice as a poem by Marlowe or Frost or Keats - I wouldn't be all that flattered if I were the woman being written about - comparing one to a horse or the other objects is not at all a compliment in my books - and more often than not in the songs - he is referring to God his beloved not a woman. It seems to me that it just might be an example of christian erotica - a man well versed and inlove and probably a little horny - the love he professes for God might be a result of halucenogenics or maybe a hidden desire for homosexuality. Those claims are about as believable as yours. As for paganism - though I don't agree with it either, it was certainly less harmful than christianity. I do however agree with you that the catholic branch of christianity is the worst of the bunch but all branches are guilty of unspeakable horror - the protestants, the quakers, the baptists, the orthodox and unorthodox etc... I think there are now 500 odd such twigs and all contain something that I disagree with. I agree also that it wasn't just christians that were ignorant and had a high rate of illiteracy but I do claim that christianity promoted such traits. Meekness and Ignorance is bliss remember? Yes, the monastaries are responsible for a lot of writing and translation and even began the first Universities in the area if you omit all those the Greeks had begun but education was limited to a select group and massive censorship was done - books were burned and we lost a great deal of invaluable information due to the Godly monks. I don;t know what it is that makes two people such as us so incredibly different in our views and I'm trying to understand it all - I would like to understand how you can take the stand you have without insulting your intelligence or claiming that your beliefs are a result of a very prejudice education - a bondage that is very difficult to break out of and a blindness that cannot see the light - Life is tough - I agree - and happiness is hard to come by at times but do you not think we'd be better off relying on our own reality than on a Reality that we have never experienced as real? <p><br>I was refering to the Israelites.  The law was handed to them.  <p>If you, and others here, interpret the Bible the way you do my postings, it's no wonder you have absolutely no idea as to the real meanings of the scriptures you sight.  If you open the Bible with your mind already made up as to it's meaning, you're just as bad as the fundamentalists who believe their churches official doctrine without ever searching for the truth on their own.  You've somehow been indoctrinated into a certain way of thinking, and nothing is going to change your mind.  So, with an angry attitude you open the bible to the Old Testament, (...atheists don't like to mess with the New Testament very much) grab a verse that seems unfair to you on it's face and run with it as proof of your own beliefs. <br> As Judy Collin's once said, "I'VE  looked at life from both sides now."  Have YOU ever tried to see the other side on any subject?<p><p>
<br>
