:  
: : I was refering to the Israelites.  The law was handed to them.  

: : If you, and others here, interpret the Bible the way you do my postings, it's no wonder you have absolutely no idea as to the real meanings of the scriptures you sight.  If you open the Bible with your mind already made up as to it's meaning, you're just as bad as the fundamentalists who believe their churches official doctrine without ever searching for the truth on their own.  You've somehow been indoctrinated into a certain way of thinking, and nothing is going to change your mind.  So, with an angry attitude you open the bible to the Old Testament, (...atheists don't like to mess with the New Testament very much) grab a verse that seems unfair to you on it's face and run with it as proof of your own beliefs. 
: :  As Judy Collin's once said, &quot;I'VE  looked at life from both sides now.&quot;  Have YOU ever tried to see the other side on any subject?

: I'm more than willing to discuss the NT as much as I do the OT. I have found nothing in either that has resulted in my doubting my beliefs. Sure, the stories in the NT aren't as cruel as those in the OT and love is much more common but still I see no evidence for the existence of God in either. The miracles Jesus performed have no proof to back them up - turning water into wine, raising the dead and healing the sick with a thought or a touch are alien concepts to science. History does seem to allow for the possibility of Jesus' existence but not as anything greater than a man - some of his teachings were quite admirable but like all philosphies - capitalism, socialism, communism, fascism etc.. they have not worked and though they may posess some useful ideas they have also been the cause of much horror. The belief that Jesus died on the cross for our sins and the belief that the Jews and Romans are evil because they killed Jesus totally contradict one another - anti-semitism was a common feeling among Christians after the crucifixion and led to much carnage but if the followers of Jesus really believed that it was God's will that caused his &quot;earthly&quot; death - then Christians should be thankful for the actions of the Jews and Romans. When I read the bibles - I read them not to prove my beliefs but to question them - I have not been an atheist all of my life and many times I have tried to believe in the Christian doctrines. My education and upbringing was in no way an atheist one and most likely any indoctrinating would have been in the other direction. It was due to independent thought that I broke away from the bondage of religion and I am very proud to call myself a freethinker. I suppose I could be compared with a fundamentalist in that my convictions are very strong but never to I profess that they are permanent - I continually question my beliefs and often I change them when they no longer agree with the evidence that we have. I have looked at the other side many times and as you advised in another post - I have also looked for God's existence with the proper attitude - I don't do any of this to prove my beliefs but so far, as this issue is involved, most of my research has had the side effect that has made my beliefs stronger as a result. I am not really angry about religion, I am more frustrated and surprised that such a concept could exist today with all that we know. I won't deny that at times I get angry about the harms I feel religion causes but I try to turn that anger into something constructive and by no means would I consider using that anger in a nasty way. We have discussed two issues in this thread - one - the likeliness or unlikeliness of God's existence - most of the information I've given on that is from science and I try to keep my personal bias out of the picture. I attempt to deal with the question in an intelligent and objective manner and am more than willing to entertain opposing evidence. The other issue is my hypothesis that religion has caused more harm than good and this is based on history, reality and my own personal observations and opinions so my prejudice is more apt to appear. I have looked at the other side of both issues however and continue to stand firm behind my beliefs. I do have an open mind Lynn and I have no qualms of giving up my beliefs or admitting that I'm wrong when the evidence is against such beliefs. I've been wrong many times - it's not something that might embarass me or make me feel less complete - in fact, I'm very much incomplete. Regardless of our differences - I wish for you a very happy and fulfilling life whether you are a christian or not - please remember that I am not attacking you personally but I am questioning your beliefs in a similar way that I question my own. 

</textarea>
<p>
